# Error Handling and Telemetry in Business Central Extensions

Production-ready BC extensions need robust error handling and observability. Let's look at the right patterns.

## TryFunctions â Your Error Safety Net

```al
procedure ProcessExternalData(DataJson: Text): Boolean
var
  ErrorText: Text;
  ProcessFailedLbl: Label 'External data processing failed: %1',
    Comment = '%1 = Error details';
begin
  if not TryParseAndProcess(DataJson) then begin
    ErrorText := GetLastErrorText();
    Message(ProcessFailedLbl, ErrorText);
    exit(false);
  end;
  exit(true);
end;

[TryFunction]
local procedure TryParseAndProcess(DataJson: Text)
var
  JObject: JsonObject;
begin
  JObject.ReadFrom(DataJson);
  // Throws inside TryFunction = caught gracefully above
  ProcessJsonData(JObject);
end;
```

## Always Use Error Labels

```al
// BAD - Hardcoded strings
Error('Customer not found');

// GOOD - Label variables for localization & consistency
var
  CustomerNotFoundErr: Label 'Customer %1 was not found in the system.',
    Comment = '%1 = Customer number';
begin
  Error(CustomerNotFoundErr, CustomerNo);
end;
```

## Custom Telemetry with Session.LogMessage

```al
procedure PostSalesDocument(var SalesHeader: Record "Sales Header")
var
  CustomDimensions: Dictionary of [Text, Text];
  PostedSuccessMsg: Label 'Sales document posted', Locked = true;
  PostFailedMsg: Label 'Sales document posting failed', Locked = true;
begin
  CustomDimensions.Add('DocumentType', Format(SalesHeader."Document Type"));
  CustomDimensions.Add('CustomerNo', SalesHeader."Sell-to Customer No.");

  if TryPostSalesDocument(SalesHeader) then
    Session.LogMessage('POST001', PostedSuccessMsg,
      Verbosity::Normal, DataClassification::SystemMetadata,
      TelemetryScope::ExtensionPublisher, CustomDimensions)
  else begin
    CustomDimensions.Add('Error', GetLastErrorText());
    Session.LogMessage('POST002', PostFailedMsg,
      Verbosity::Error, DataClassification::SystemMetadata,
      TelemetryScope::ExtensionPublisher, CustomDimensions);
  end;
end;
```

## Connecting to Azure Application Insights

Add to your `app.json`:
```json
{
  "applicationInsightsKey": "your-instrumentation-key-here"
}
```

Then filter your telemetry in Azure Monitor:
```kusto
traces
| where customDimensions.extensionPublisher == 'YourCompany'
| where message startswith 'POST'
| project timestamp, message, customDimensions
| order by timestamp desc
```

# Building API Pages for External Integrations

Business Central's API pages expose your data as OData v4 endpoints, enabling seamless integration with Power BI, Power Automate, and external systems.

## Basic API Page Structure

```al
page 50200 "Customer API"
{
  PageType = API;
  APIPublisher = 'yourcompany';
  APIGroup = 'core';
  APIVersion = 'v1.0';
  EntityName = 'customer';
  EntitySetName = 'customers';
  SourceTable = Customer;
  DelayedInsert = true;
  ODataKeyFields = SystemId;

  layout
  {
    area(Content)
    {
      group(General)
      {
        field(id; Rec.SystemId)
        {
          Caption = 'Id';
          Editable = false;
        }
        field(number; Rec."No.")
        {
          Caption = 'Number';
        }
        field(displayName; Rec.Name)
        {
          Caption = 'Display Name';
        }
        field(email; Rec."E-Mail")
        {
          Caption = 'Email';
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

## Accessing the Endpoint

```http
GET https://api.businesscentral.dynamics.com/v2.0/{tenantId}/{environment}/api/yourcompany/core/v1.0/companies({companyId})/customers
```

## Adding Filtering Support

OData filtering works automatically:
```http
GET /customers?$filter=country eq 'GB'&$top=50&$orderby=displayName
```

## Securing Your API

- Use **OAuth 2.0** with Azure AD app registration
- Apply **permission sets** to control access
- Consider **rate limiting** for external consumers

## Best Practices

1. Always use `SystemId` (GUID) as the OData key â never use business keys like document numbers
2. Use `DelayedInsert = true` for API pages to handle complex insertions
3. Implement proper error handling with meaningful error messages
4. Version your APIs (`v1.0`, `v2.0`) to avoid breaking changes

# Optimizing AL Code for Performance

Poor performance is one of the most common issues in Business Central extensions. This guide covers the most impactful optimizations.

## Filter Early, Filter Often

The golden rule: **filter data before you loop through it**.

```al
// BAD - Fetches all customers, checks in AL
Customer.FindSet();
repeat
  if Customer."Country/Region Code" = 'GB' then
    ProcessCustomer(Customer);
until Customer.Next() = 0;

// GOOD - SQL does the filtering
Customer.SetRange("Country/Region Code", 'GB');
if Customer.FindSet() then
  repeat
    ProcessCustomer(Customer);
  until Customer.Next() = 0;
```

## Use Temporary Tables

```al
var
  TempSalesLine: Record "Sales Line" temporary;
begin
  // Load filtered data once
  SalesLine.SetRange("Document No.", SalesHeader."No.");
  if SalesLine.FindSet() then
    repeat
      TempSalesLine := SalesLine;
      TempSalesLine.Insert();
    until SalesLine.Next() = 0;

  // Process from temp table (fast, in-memory)
  if TempSalesLine.FindSet() then
    repeat
      // Process...
    until TempSalesLine.Next() = 0;
end;
```

## Avoid CalcFields in Loops

```al
// BAD - Database hit on every iteration
repeat
  Customer.CalcFields("Balance (LCY)"); // Expensive!
  if Customer."Balance (LCY)" > 10000 then
    SendAlert(Customer);
until Customer.Next() = 0;

// GOOD - Use FlowFields with SetAutoCalcFields
Customer.SetAutoCalcFields("Balance (LCY)");
Customer.FindSet();
repeat
  if Customer."Balance (LCY)" > 10000 then
    SendAlert(Customer);
until Customer.Next() = 0;
```

## Key Performance Tips

| Pattern | Performance | Note |
|---------|-------------|------|
| `FindSet()` + loop | Fast | Best for reading multiple records |
| `Get()` | Very fast | Single record by primary key |
| `FindFirst()` | Moderate | Adds `TOP 1` to SQL |
| `Count()` | Slow | Full table scan without filter |
| `CalcFields` in loop | Very slow | Avoid! |

## Profiling Your Code

Use the **AL Profiler** in VS Code to identify bottlenecks:
1. Open Command Palette â `AL: Start CPU Profile`
2. Perform the slow operation
3. Stop the profile and analyze the flamegraph

# Event-Driven Programming Patterns in AL

One of the most powerful patterns in Business Central development is **event-driven programming**. It allows you to extend standard functionality without touching Microsoft's base application code.

## Why Events Matter

Instead of modifying the standard `Sales-Post` codeunit, you subscribe to events it publishes. This means:
- Your code survives Microsoft updates
- Multiple extensions can hook into the same event
- Clean separation of concerns

## Integration Events

```al
codeunit 50101 "Order Processing"
{
  procedure ProcessOrder(var SalesHeader: Record "Sales Header")
  var
    IsHandled: Boolean;
  begin
    OnBeforeProcessOrder(SalesHeader, IsHandled);
    if IsHandled then
      exit;

    // Core processing logic
    DoProcessOrder(SalesHeader);

    OnAfterProcessOrder(SalesHeader);
  end;

  [IntegrationEvent(false, false)]
  procedure OnBeforeProcessOrder(var SalesHeader: Record "Sales Header"; var IsHandled: Boolean)
  begin
  end;

  [IntegrationEvent(false, false)]
  procedure OnAfterProcessOrder(var SalesHeader: Record "Sales Header")
  begin
  end;
}
```

## Event Subscribers

```al
codeunit 50102 "Custom Validation Handler"
{
  [EventSubscriber(ObjectType::Codeunit, Codeunit::"Order Processing",
    OnBeforeProcessOrder, '', false, false)]
  local procedure ValidateOrderOnBeforeProcess(
    var SalesHeader: Record "Sales Header";
    var IsHandled: Boolean)
  begin
    if SalesHeader."Sell-to Customer No." = '' then
      Error('Customer number is required before processing.');
  end;
}
```

## Best Practices

1. **Always use the Handled pattern** for events where subscribers might want to cancel default processing
2. **Name events clearly**: `OnBefore...` and `OnAfter...` conventions
3. **Pass records by reference** when subscribers need to modify them
4. **Document your integration events** with XML comments for other developers
